<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-08-23T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-08-23T16:00:00-05:00" n="234" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d234">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">033.1193 Nelson, Donald M./8–2344:
                        Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-23T17:00:00-04:00">August 23,
                                1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1113. Mr. Donald Nelson is travelling with General Hurley to China but it is
                        anticipated that he will remain there only 2 or 3 weeks (Department’s 1094,
                        August 19). Specifically he is to look into the problem of civilian supply
                        to China “over the hump” and into the related problems of production and
                        distribution in China. If time and opportunity make it possible he may also
                        conduct some investigation into economic problems relating to reconstruction
                        in China. Mr. Nelson will be accompanied by his special assistant, E. A.
                        Locke, Jr.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>